    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="266"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d266">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.51W89 Belgium/264</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Economic Adviser</hi> (<hi rend="italic"
                        >Feis</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-05">June 5,
                            1935</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>By instruction of the Secretary, I put before the Belgian Ambassador this morning
                    the suggestion that his Government consider making some payment to this
                    Government on debt account in the form of delivery of radium to be used in
                    American hospitals and similar institutions for humanitarian purposes. I
                    explained the thought underlying this proposal in substantially the same terms
                    as was explained to the British Ambassador. In response to his question as to
                    whether similar suggestions were being put before other governments. I informed
                    him for the confidential information of his Government that a proposal of
                    similar import had been transmitted to the British Government. I explained that
                    in selecting these two governments in this first approach on the subject we had
                    been guided by the fact that the materials in question seemed most clearly
                    desirable and the operation most feasible, and that no other strategic idea had
                    presented itself. He said he would convey the suggestion to his Government
                    promptly, and was sure that it would receive the most thoughtful
                    consideration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>H[<hi rend="smallcaps">erbert</hi>] F[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >eis</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
